data.content:
Yes! In MSTest 3.7+, use **ValueTuples** instead of `object[]` for type safety and cleaner syntax:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Benefits:**
- Compile-time type checking (no runtime casts from `object`)
- Named tuple elements serve as documentation
- Mismatched types caught at build time, not test time

For this simple case, `[DataRow]` also works well:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

Use `DynamicData` with tuples when you need complex types that `DataRow` can't handle (objects, collections, decimals).
